@tqchen, I digged more. Seems like the problem happens in `RebaseNonZeroMinLoop()` (which is called by `Schedule::normalize()`). Here is the initial part of `RebaseNonZeroMinLoop()`.
```c++
void RebaseNonZeroMinLoop(const Schedule& sch) {
  std::unordered_map<IterVar, IterVar> rebase_map;
  for (Stage s : sch->stages) {
    if (s->attach_type == kInlinedAlready) continue;

    auto root_iter_vars = s->op->root_iter_vars();
    ArrayNode* leaf_vars = s->leaf_iter_vars.CopyOnWrite();
    for (IterVar iv : root_iter_vars) {
      size_t idx = FindNodeRef(leaf_vars, iv);
      auto it  = s->iter_var_attrs.find(iv);
      // don;t need to rebase path that are binded.
      if (it != s->iter_var_attrs.end() &&
          (*it).second->bind_thread.defined()) {
        continue;
      }
      if (idx < leaf_vars->data.size()) {
        // insert rebase
        IterVar rebased = IterVarNode::make(
            Range(), iv->var.copy_with_suffix(""), iv->iter_type);
        s->relations.push_back(RebaseNode::make(iv, rebased));
        if (s->iter_var_attrs.count(iv)) {
          s->iter_var_attrs.Set(rebased, s->iter_var_attrs.at(iv));
        }
        leaf_vars->data[idx] = rebased.node_;
        rebase_map[iv] = rebased;
      }
    }
  }
/* the rest of the method */
}
```

For the specific test case above, what happens is that before `RebaseNonZeroLoop`, there is a stage (call it `s1`) in which both `leaf_iter_vars` and `all_iter_vars` refer to the same pair of `IterVar`s.
After the loop above that goes over the stages, stage `s1` is modified as follows: Each of the two `IterVar`s of `leaf_iter_vars` are replaced by another newly created `IterVar` ([see this line](https://github.com/dmlc/tvm/blob/8a3dbd7971a3d7df7c3a728d18c7c6124bf68989/src/schedule/schedule_dataflow_rewrite.cc#L258). However, the two `IterVar`s in `s1.all_iter_vars` stay as before. Therefore, `all_iter_vars` end up referring to two different pairs of `IterVar`s causing problems later on.
It seems to me that the solution is to make the `IterVar` replacement everywhere in the stage when we replace it in `leaf_iter_vars`. How can this be done properly?

This is related to #738 in the sense that we have stale `IterVar`s here and there, AFAIK, we have stale tensors.
